It is the responsibility of schools to teach children good behavior in addition to providing formal education. To what extent do you agree or disagree

It is widely argued that schools play a crucial role in shaping children’s behavior as well as providing academic instruction. I strongly agree that schools should take responsibility for teaching good behavior; however, I believe this role must be shared with families and the wider community to be fully effective.

On the one hand, schools are uniquely positioned to promote positive behavior in a structured and consistent environment. By incorporating moral education into the curriculum, students can develop essential values such as honesty, respect, and empathy. Moreover, clear rules and codes of conduct help establish expectations for appropriate behavior, encouraging discipline and mutual respect among students. Teachers also serve as important role models, demonstrating appropriate ways to communicate and resolve conflicts. For example, when educators handle disputes calmly and fairly, students learn constructive approaches to managing disagreements, which contributes to a more harmonious school environment.

On the other hand, it would be unrealistic to expect schools to bear this responsibility alone. Children’s behavior is significantly influenced by their upbringing and home environment, where fundamental values are first formed. If parental guidance is inconsistent with what is taught at school, children may struggle to develop a clear understanding of acceptable behavior. In addition, schools often face limitations in terms of time, resources, and staff training, which can restrict their ability to provide comprehensive character education. Without support from families and communities, efforts made by schools may have only a limited impact.

In conclusion, while I strongly agree that schools should actively teach good behavior alongside academic subjects, this responsibility should not rest solely on educational institutions. A collaborative approach involving parents and society is essential to ensure that children develop into well-rounded and responsible individuals.
